of 4 to 6 inches and ice accumulations of a light glaze. Winds
gusting as high as 40 mph.

* WHEN...From 6 AM Wednesday to 6 PM CST Thursday.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...This will be a long duration event.

Wednesday, before changing to all snow Wednesday night. Winds
will increase Wednesday afternoon producing areas of blowing
snow.

* WHAT...Snow. Additional snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches
along and east of Highway 93. Across western and central
portions of Northern Elko County (including the Mountain City
and Wildhorse areas) additional snow accumulations of 3 to 10
inches are expected, with higher amounts in the mountains.

* WHERE...Northern Elko County.

* WHEN...Until 10 PM PST this evening.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult due to slippery roads,
reduced visibilities, and possibly drifting of snow. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The combination of recent snow or slush
along with the new snowfall, and near to below freezing
temperatures, will keep many roadways slippery through this
evening. Blowing and drifting of snow is possible in valleys,
and likely across mountains and higher summits where winds
will be strongest.

* WHAT...Snow and blowing snow expected. Total snow accumulations
of 3 To 6 inches. Winds gusting as high as 40 mph.

* WHERE...From Dillingham west.

* WHEN...From 3 AM to 6 PM AKST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on difficult travel. Areas of blowing snow
could significantly reduce visibility to a half mile.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The strongest winds near the coast will
produce areas of blowing snow with visibilities down to a half
mile from Dillingham and west towards Togiak. Snow is likely to
continue into Sunday and perhaps Monday with more accumulating
snow expected.

* WHAT...Snow and blowing snow expected. Total snow accumulations
of 2 to 4 inches. Winds gusting as high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...Kuskokwim Delta.

* WHEN...From midnight tonight to 3 PM AKST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on difficult travel. Areas of blowing snow could
significantly reduce visibility to a half mile. Gusty winds may
create higher surf and elevated water levels along the coast.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The strongest winds will be along the
coast. Expect gusts up to 45 mph inland, including areas around
Bethel. Temperatures will warm into the low to mid 30s and winds
will diminish Saturday afternoon with the blowing snow threat
ending.

* WHAT...A period of heavy, wet snow expected. Total snow
accumulations of 2 to 4 inches.

* WHERE...Winnebago, Boone, McHenry and Lake IL Counties.

* WHEN...From 3 AM to 1 PM CST Friday.

* IMPACTS...Expect periods of sharply reduced visibilities and
hazardous travel due to slushy snow accumulations. The
hazardous conditions will likely impact portions of the morning
commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Temperatures are expected to warm above
freezing through the late morning and afternoon with road
conditions likely to quickly improve as snow ends.

.OVERVIEW...A band of snow can be seen on radar across central
Iowa this evening and will continue to spread across northeast
Iowa and southeast Minnesota this evening. This band of snow is
expected to reach US 218 around 10 PM tonight, US 63 around 11 PM
and US 52 around midnight. Further to the east, snow will reach
the Interstate 94 corridor early Friday morning. Freezing drizzle
is still expected to spread across the area as the snow comes to
an end Friday morning. Light ice accumulations are possible, but
impacts are expected to be limited as the drizzle falls on a fresh
snowpack.

* WHAT...Snow, heavy at times, followed by freezing drizzle

* WHERE...Portions of north central and northeast Iowa and

minor coastal flooding.

Iowa late this evening and will reach the Interstate 94 corridor
in central Wisconsin early Friday morning. Freezing drizzle is
expected to spread across the area as the snow comes to an end
Friday morning. Light ice accumulations are possible, but impacts
are expected to be limited as the drizzle falls on a fresh
snowpack.

county: Northern and Eastern Klamath County and Western Lake County
description:
* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow snow accumulations of 3 to
8 inches. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph will result in
reduced visibility due to blowing snow.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, snow possible. Total snow
accumulations of 2 to 9 inches possible. Winds could gust as
high as 60 mph that will result in reduced visibility due to
blowing snow.

* WHERE...
-For the Advisory, the higher terrain and backcountry of
Northern and Eastern Klamath County and Western Lake County.

-For the Winter Weather Watch, all areas of Eastern Klamath
County and Western Lake County. This includes highway 140 and
Bly Mountain & Quartz Mountain summit, Bly, Beatty, Crescent,
and Highways 97 and 31.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 10 AM this
morning to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch,
from Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible.

-Snow: Blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility.

-Wind: Strong, gusty south winds could bring down tree branches
and create very difficult driving conditions for high profile
vehicles.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The main hazard driving the Winter Storm
Watch is the combination of wind and snow creating the potential
for blowing snow to lead to reduced visibility.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow accumulations of 6 to 10
inches. Winds gusting as high as 35 mph that could lead to
reduced visibility due to blowing snow.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy snow possible. Total snow
accumulations of 7 to 15 inches possible. Winds could gust as
high as 45 mph and likely result in reduced visibility due to
blowing snow.

* WHERE...Central Oregon Cascades. During the Advisory, Eastern
Douglas County and NW Klamath County including, Diamond Lake
Pass, highways 230, 138 (up to the intersection with highway

highway 138 east of the intersection with highway 230.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 10 AM this
morning to 10 PM PST this evening. For the Winter Storm Watch,
from Friday afternoon through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. Gusty
winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The main impact during the advisor will be
from 10 AM to 4 PM PST when snowfall rates are at their highest
and the winds peak. There is only a 10% chance that rates will
reach one inch per hour at this time though.

and Hyder. As of 7 PM Wednesday, Haines Customs had measured 8
inches of snow while Haines Airport received rain. As of 3 AM
Thursday, Hyder measured 3.2 inches. Light snow will continue for
Haines Customs and Hyder with additional snow amounts between 1
to 3 inches Thursday.

* WHAT...Additional snow accumulations of 3 to 5 inches through
early morning.

* WHERE...Haines Highway west of Haines.

* WHEN...Until 6 AM AKST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The highest snow accumulations are expected
along the Haines Highway from mile marker 20 to the border. As
of 7 PM Wedesday, webcam imagery and spotter reports confirm
that appreciable snowfall continues to occur with around 9
inches of snow on the ground. Snowfall intensities are expected
to diminish later this evening into the early morning hours
Thursday.

* WHAT...Snow is occurring. Additional snow accumulations of 5
to 8 inches expected through tonight with total snow
accumulations of 10 to 13 inches expected through early
Thursday morning.

* WHERE...City of Hyder.

* WHEN...Until 6 AM AKST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult in places.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Steady snow accumulation continues and is
expected to continue through Thursday morning. Heaviest
snowfall totals are expected overnight going into early
Thursday morning.

* WHAT...Snow. Additional snow accumulations of up to two inches.

* WHERE...Uncompahgre Plateau and Dallas Divide.

* WHEN...Until 6 AM MST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. A detailed map of
the snowfall can be found at: www.weather.gov/gjt/winter.

* WHAT...For the Winter Weather Advisory above 2500 feet, snow
expected. Total snow accumulations of up to 7 inches. For the
Winter Storm Watch above 2500 feet, heavy snow possible. Total
snow accumulations of 7 to 24 inches possible. Winds could
gust as high as 35 mph.

* WHERE...Northern Trinity County.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through late Saturday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute.

county: North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County
description:
* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow expected. Total
snow accumulations of 5 to 10 inches. Winds gusting as high as
45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible.
Total snow accumulations of 4 to 19 inches possible. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County. This
includes Pondosa, Tennant, and Bray.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, Snow expected with
accumulations of 4 to 8 inches expected, with higher amounts
above 4500 feet, and winds gusting as high as 35 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch above 3000 feet, heavy wet snow
possible, with snow accumulations of 5 to 15 inches. Higher snow
amounts will be possible in the higher terrain up to 25 inches.
Winds could gust as high as 50 mph and cause reduced visibility
due to blowing snow.

* WHERE...Western Siskiyou County, including highway 3 south of
Callahan. For the Winter Weather Watch, this also includes
Fort Jones.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Gusty winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High snowfall rates of 1/hr are likely

description:
* WHAT...Snow expected with accumulations of 5 to 9 inches and
winds gusting as high as 40 mph that could cause blowing snow.

* WHERE...Eastern Diamond Lake and NW Klamath County including,
Diamond Lake including highway 230, 138. Crater Lake NP.

* WHEN...From 4 AM to 10 PM PST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions and reduced
visibility due to blowing snow.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The main impact during the advisory is
from 10 AM to 4 PM PST when snowfall rates are at their
highest and winds peak. There is only a 10% chance that rates
reach one inch per hour at this time though.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow accumulations up to 4
inches for elevations above 3500 feet. Winds gusting as high as
45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible, with
accumulations of 2 to 8 inches possible around the valley floor,
and higher amounts in the higher terrain. Winds could gust as
high as 60 mph and is likely to cause reduced  from blowing
snow.

* WHERE...The Shasta Valley and I-5 near Hilt, near the highway
96 & 263 exit, and near Weed.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy

hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* WHERE...Eastern Diamond Lake and NW Klamath County including,

county: North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County
description:
* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow expected. Total
snow accumulations of 5 to 10 inches. Winds gusting as high as
45 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy wet snow possible.
Total snow accumulations of 4 to 19 inches possible. Winds
could gust as high as 60 mph.

* WHERE...North Central and Southeast Siskiyou County. This
includes Pondosa, Tennant, and Bray.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Strong winds could cause tree damage.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr

* WHAT...
-For the Winter Weather Advisory, Snow expected with
accumulations of 4 to 8 inches expected, with higher amounts
above 4500 feet, and winds gusting as high as 35 mph.

-For the Winter Storm Watch above 3000 feet, heavy wet snow
possible, with snow accumulations of 5 to 15 inches. Higher snow
amounts will be possible in the higher terrain up to 25 inches.
Winds could gust as high as 50 mph and cause reduced visability
due to blowing snow.

* WHERE...Western Siskiyou County, including highway 3 south of
Callahan. For the Winter Weather Watch, this also includes Fort
Jones.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 10 PM PST
Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday afternoon
through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible. Patchy
blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The
hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening
commute. Gusty winds could bring down tree branches.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...High snowfall rates of 1/hr are likely

* WHAT...Additional snow accumulations of 3 to 5 inches through
early morning.

* WHERE...Haines Highway west of Haines.

* WHEN...Until midnight AKST Wednesday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The highest snow accumulations are expected
along the Haines Highway from mile marker 20 to the border. As

inches of snow on the ground. Snowfall intensities are expected
to diminish later this evening into the early morning hours
Thursday.

* WHAT...For the Wind Chill Advisory, very cold wind chills. Wind
chills as low as 30 below zero. For the Winter Weather Advisory,
blowing and drifting snow expected. Winds gusting as high as 45
mph.

* WHERE...Eastern Glacier, Western Toole, and Central Pondera.

* WHEN...For the Wind Chill Advisory, until 11 AM MST Wednesday. For
the Winter Weather Advisory, from 6 AM to 5 PM MST Wednesday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The dangerously cold
wind chills tonight and Wednesday morning could cause frostbite on
exposed skin in as little as 30 minutes. Blowing and drifting snow
on Wednesday may significantly reduce visibility and cause partial
lane blockages.

description:
* WHAT...Snow occurring. Total snow accumulations of 6 to 10
inches.

* WHERE...Anchorage.

* WHEN...From 3 PM this afternoon to 4 PM AKST Wednesday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous
conditions could impact the Tuesday evening and Wednesday
morning commutes.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Expect periods of mostly light snow today.
Snow will intensify during the late afternoon hours, with the
heaviest snow expected this evening through early Wednesday
morning. Snow will then linger through the day Wednesday,
especially near the mountains.

* WHAT...Snow occurring. Additional snow accumulations of up to 5
inches along the coast and up to 11 inches inland.

* WHERE...Western Kenai Peninsula.

* WHEN...From noon today to noon AKST Wednesday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous
conditions could impact the morning commute.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Expect periods of light snow this afternoon.
A band of heavier snow will then form midday along the Inlet
and Sterling highway corridor Anchor Point to Kenai. This band
will move inland by this evening, with snow near the Inlet
lightening up or even ending in some areas. The heaviest snow is
expected east of Soldotna along the Sterling Highway from late
this afternoon through Wednesday morning.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 3 to 6
inches.

* WHERE...Haines Borough and Klukwan.

* WHEN...From 6 AM Wednesday to midnight AKST Wednesday night.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Highest accumulations expected on the
Haines Highway. The city of Haines will likely see around 2 to 4
inches before warming up enough Wed to start to mix with or
change to rain. Accumulations there will be highly dependent on
the timing of the warmup.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 10 to 13
inches.

* WHERE...City of Hyder.

* WHEN...From 6 PM this evening to 6 AM AKST Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult to impossible.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Steady snow accumulations through Thu
morning expected. Snow may mix with rain Wed afternoon before
going back to snow.

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches
